    "Craig S. Keener": "Valler, Shulamit. 1995 \"The Number Fourteen as a Literary Device in the Babylonian Talmud.\" Journal for the Study of Judaism 26: 169-",
    "Dr. Peter S. Ruckman": "There are seven oaks in the Old [v_Gen_35_4] Testament. They are in Genesis 35:4, 8; 1 Samuel 31:13; Joshua [v_2Sa_18_9] 24:26; 2 Samuel 18:9; Judges 6:11; and 1 Kings 13:14. \u201cAnd they journeyed: and the terror of God was upon the cities that were round about them\u201d (vs. 5). Jacob `[char_Jacob_Ref]` had nothing to fear. Instead of massing for an attack on Jacob `[char_Jacob_Ref]`, the Perizzites and Canaanites pulled back from the whole affair. When Jacob `[char_Jacob_Ref]`\u2019s caravan went by their fields, they acted like they were busy picking cotton and \u201cknew nothing about it.\u201d \u201cThey did not pursue after the sons of Jacob `[char_Jacob_Ref]`\u201d (vs. 5). Jacob `[char_Jacob_Ref]` gets back to Bethel without a casualty (vs. 6) and builds an altar as God commanded him (vs. 7). This time he calls it [v_Gen_28_19] \u201cEl-beth-el\u201d instead of \u201cBeth-el.\u201d (See comments on Gen. 28:19.) God always comes first before the \u201chouse of God.\u201d Where the order is reversed\u2014like a liberal reverses the first two commandments of [v_Mat_22_37] Matthew 22:37\u201339\u2014the lost sinner is led to a sacrament or an institution instead of a Living Saviour and Loving Lord. In",
    "Commentary Vol. 83": "And the sons of Zilpah, etc.] And lastly, the sons of Zilpah, Leah\u2019s handmaid, which were two also, Gad and Asher `[char_Asher_Gen_30]`; it is added, these [are] the sons of Jacob `[char_Jacob_Ref]`, which were born to him in Padanaram, all excepting Benjamin; and because they were by far the greater part, even all but one, that were born there, this is said in general; and there having been given in the context such a particular account of the birth of Benjamin, and of the place of it, them was no need for the historian particularly to except him, since the reader would be in no danger of being led into a mistake.\nVer.",
