    "Craig S. Keener": "Edited by J. Van der Ploeg. Leiden: \u0395. J. Brill. Van der Woude, A. S. 1982 \"Wicked Priest or Wicked Priests? Reflections on the Identification of the Wicked Priest in the Habakkuk Commentary.\" Journal of Jewish Studies 33: 349-\n2. Missoula, MT: Scholars Press. Williamson, H. G. M. 1982 1 and 2 Chronicles. New Century Bible Commentary. Grand Rapids: Eerdmans; London: Marshall, Morgan & Scott. Willis, Geoffrey G. 1975 \"Lead Us Not Into Temptation.\" Downside Review 93: 281-",
    "Dr. Peter S. Ruckman": "By saying that the wicked do NOT suffer for their sins and then by saying that he himself (Job) was suffering with \u201cno profit\u201d after obeying God (vs. 3), Job had practically said, \u201cI AM RIGHT AND GOD IS WRONG.\u201d Now, this is what every American in this century is saying if he accepts his church, sacraments, ideology, philosophy, religion, tradition, good works, or moral standards (or \u201cbeliefs\u201d) as a basis of justification before God. You see, Romans 10:1\u20134 makes it quite clear that the morally righteous man, who is sincerely and zealously seeking to \u201cbe good,\u201d is actually a man who is engaged in making a LIAR out of God by pitting the frail, puny, fallible \u201cgoodness\u201d of his own human nature against the goodness of a holy, omnipotent Lord. If Christ is God\u2019s righteousness (Rom. 10:1\u20134), what is YOUR righteousness? Answer: filthy rags (Isa. 64:6). You couldn\u2019t be as righteous as God (let alone MORE righteous) if you could charge to your credit every good deed committed by St. Francis, Florence Nightingale, Churchill, Kagawa, Peale, Gandhi, Mann, Madam Curie, Father Damien, and Livingstone in their lifetimes. (See Tell It Like It Is , 1969.) Although Job, as any modern Campbellite elder or Catholic priest, has been very careful not to say: \u201cGod you\u2019re wrong and I\u2019m right,\u201d he has clearly done three things:\n2. Stated how good he was (Job 31) to show how he deserved better treatment.\n2. God is immune from actual injury whether a man lives right or not (vs. 6: see 34:33).\n2. By saying that the wicked do NOT suffer for their sins and then by saying that he himself (Job) was suffering with \u201cno profit\u201d after obeying God (vs. 3), Job had practically said, \u201cI AM RIGHT AND GOD IS WRONG.\u201d Now, this is what every American in this century is saying if he accepts his church, sacraments, ideology, philosophy, religion, tradition, good works, or moral standards (or \u201cbeliefs\u201d) as a basis of [v_Rom_10_1] justification before God. You see, Romans 10:1\u20134 makes it quite clear that the morally righteous man, who is sincerely and zealously seeking to \u201cbe good,\u201d is actually a man who is engaged in making a LIAR out of God by pitting the frail, puny, fallible \u201cgoodness\u201d of his own human nature against the goodness of a holy, omnipotent Lord. [v_Rom_10_1] If Christ is God\u2019s righteousness (Rom. 10:1\u20134), what is YOUR [v_Isa_64_6] righteousness? Answer: filthy rags (Isa. 64:6). You couldn\u2019t be as righteous as God (let alone MORE righteous) if you could charge to your credit every good deed committed by St. Francis, Florence Nightingale, Churchill, Kagawa, Peale, Gandhi, Mann, Madam Curie, Father Damien, and Livingstone in their lifetimes. (See Tell It Like It Is, 1969.) Although Job, as any modern Campbellite elder or Catholic priest, has been very careful not to say: \u201cGod you\u2019re wrong and I\u2019m right,\u201d he has clearly done three things:\n2. Stated how good he was (Job 31) to show how he deserved better treatment.\n2. God is immune from actual injury whether a man lives right or not (vs. 6: see 34:33).",
    "Commentary Vol. 83": "Then Jacob `[char_Jacob_Ref]` said unto his household, etc.] His wives and children; and to all that [were] with him; his menservants and maidservants, and such as remained with him of the captives of Shechem, who might choose to continue with him: put away the strange gods that [are] among you; meaning not the teraphim or images of Laban\u2019s, which Rachel had stolen from him; for it can hardly be thought that these should be retained so many years in Jacob `[char_Jacob_Ref]`\u2019s family, and used in an idolatrous manner; but rather such as might be among the Canaanitish servants that had been lately taken into Jacob `[char_Jacob_Ref]`\u2019s service, or that were among the captives of Shechem, or taken along with the spoil of that city; and so the Targum of Jonathan calls them the idols of the people, which they brought from the idols\u2019 temple at Shechem; and the words may be rendered, \u201cthe gods of the strangers\u201d f1576, that is, of the Shechemites, who were Heathens and aliens, strangers to the true God, the knowledge and worship of him: and be clean; either by abstaining from their wives, as some interpret it, [v_Exo_19_10] from (<021910>Exodus 19:10,15); or rather by washing their bodies, as Aben Ezra gives the sense of it; their hands were full of the blood of the 609 Shechemites, and needed to be washed and purified, as the Targum of Jonathan has it, from the pollutions of the slain, before they went to Bethel, the house of God; and these outward ablutions and purifications were significative of inward cleansing by the grace of God, and of outward [v_Isa_1_15] reformation of life and manners; (see <230115>Isaiah `[char_Isaiah_Gen_26]` 1:15,16); and change your garments: which might be stained with blood, and therefore not fit to appear in before God, or were old and worn out, or sordid apparel: changing and washing of garments were also emblems of renewing of the mind, and cleansing of the soul, and of the change of heart and life, as well as of pleasure, delight, and cheerfulness in appearing before God.\nVer."
